entry.title: [Thumbnail Cache] Improve refetch logic to minimize ETC1 decompression
entry.content:
ETC1 decompression is quite slow and we are doing it needlessly for

refetch when no thumbnail exists. Avoid this by creating a more robust

JPEG refetch path that waits for a thumbnail to be available.



We cannot remove ETC1 refetch entirely yet because of how aspect ratio

is currently used.



I'm working on a future patchset to either

* Ignore aspect ratio for refetch entirely

OR

* Wait for a new JPEG if the aspect ratio is very off. And falling back

to the existing JPEG otherwise.



However these depend on changing how we treat aspect ratio on phones

from a fixed value to something dynamic based on screen size. It will

also depend upon potentially storing a larger JPEG and scaling/cropping

it to fit on the GTS. This is already partially supported, but requires

tweaks to not enforce any aspect ratio and just use the native thumbnail

resolution.

entry.title: Revert "Clean up a pending commit RenderFrameHosts if the renderer crashes."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 001887f0c1182d326e664dc30b51846e6b35641e.



Reason for revert: probably causing crashes when site isolation is not

enabled. Example failure:

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/android-bfcache-rel/21415/overview



Original change's description:

> Clean up a pending commit RenderFrameHosts if the renderer crashes.

>

> When a RenderFrameHost's render process crashes, `RenderProcessGone()`

> marks the RenderFrameHost as "must be replaced". If the RenderFrameHost

> is in the speculative state, `RenderProcessGone()` also destroys `this`,

> since a speculative RenderFrameHost with a crashed renderer can

> never successfully commit a navigation.

>

> `RenderFrameHostManager::GetFrameHostForNavigation()` asserts that this

> cleanup happens by DCHECKing that `speculative_render_frame_host_`, if

> any, is not marked as "must be replaced".

>

> However, this cleanup step only applied to speculative RFHs before they

> entered the commit commit state; after entering the pending commit

> state, the RFH would be marked as "must be replaced" but would not be

> destroyed, tripping the DCHECK in `GetFrameHostForNavigation()`.

>

> The fix is also destroy pending commit RFHs when the renderer process

> crashes; similarly to speculative RFHs, they can no longer successfully

> commit a navigation.

>

> This ends up being a bit tricky due to tripping another DCHECK though:

> RenderFrameHostImpl's destructor calls `ResetOwnedNavigationRequests()`,

> which DCHECKs that, when navigation queueing is enabled, the reason for

> resetting the navigation requests is the render process is gone or the

> frame tree node is being removed. This DCHECK is intended to prevent

> bugs where the pending commit RFH is unintentionally destroyed instead

> of waiting for the pending commit to complete.

>

> But since C++ destructors do not take any arguments, the destructor

> always passes kRenderFrameHostDestruction as the reason to discard those

> navigations, even though the *caller* knows that the *actual* reason is

> kRenderProcessGone, which trips the aforementioned DCHECK when

> destroying the pending commit RFH.

>

> To fix this this DCHECK, `UnsetSpeculativeRenderFrameHost()` now

> advances the lifecycle state to `kReadyToBeDeleted` to explicitly signal

> that it is OK to delete the RFH, despite the fact that was in the

> pending commit state.

>

entry.title: FSA: Do not create an empty swap file if keepExistingData is false
entry.content:
Historically, calling createWritable() would:



1. Create an empty swap file

2. If keepExistingData, try to copy the contents of the source file



This leaves us with an empty swap file if the copy fails, such as if

the source file does not exist. After this CL, that process becomes:



0. Take a lock on the swap file (as of https://crrev.com/c/4521555)

1. If keepExistingData, check whether the swap file exists. If not,

copy or clone the source file to the swap file

2. Else, create an empty swap file



This technically opens the door for TOCTOU issues if the swap file is

created between the existence check and when the file is copied, but

- this is unlikely given that the swap file is locked

(i.e. the changes would need to come from elsewhere)

- on Mac, file cloning only succeeds if the destination file does not

exist. So some TOCTOU risk is unavoidable (and we fall back to

create + copy in this case anyways)



Newly passes a WPT that was failing because the empty swap file was

not being cleaned up



Bug: 1405851, 1413443

entry.title: Android: Add HDR support
entry.content:
HDR content on Android is put into a buffer that is like a normal

SDR buffer (e,g, 8 or 10 bit unorm, sRGB or P3 colors space), except

the buffer has a "gain" applied to it. This gain can be expressed

as a custom skcms_TransferFunction for an SkColorSpace or

gfx::ColorSpace.



In DisplayAndroidManager::DoUpdateDisplay, we populate a

gfx::DisplayColorSpaces. This structure lists the gfx::ColorSpace and

buffer formats to use for sRGB, wide color gamut SDR, and HDR content.

Populate the HDR gfx::ColorSpace with a copy of the gfx::ColorSpace

used for wide color gamut content, scaled by the maximum allowable

gain.



In SurfaceControl::Transaction::SetColorSpace, we need to communicate

this gain. Extract the gain from the gfx::ColorSpace. Do this by

updating the function ColorSpaceToADataSpace to detect scaled

transfer functions when translating them to Android transfer functions.

Add a bunch of tests for ColorSpaceToADataSpace, now that it is more

complicated than it used to be.



In viz::SkiaRenderer::FinishDrawingFrame, set the desired HDR headroom

based on whether or not the content being drawn is HDR. Note that this

information (gfx::ContentColorUsage) is binary, and as a result we are

forced to chose an arbitrary desired headroom. We go with 1000/203,

which corresponds to HLG and most PQ content.

entry.title: Removes -_self value from target attribute since it is the default
entry.content:
In https://crrev.com/c/4508963, the "target" attribute was exposed to IA2 and ATK

clients, for and elements, in order to allow screen readers to provide

the appropriate announcement to their users.



The "-self" attribute value is the same as empty and is the

default value for the "target" attribute.

In order to save memory in the accessibility tree,

as well as speed up serialization / deserialization

of the tree when moving through process boundaries,

"_self" is not stored in the tree.

entry.title: Re-enable ChromeVisibilityObserverInteractiveTest
entry.content:
Basically, when closing a window and switching to another window, two

notifications will be sent out quickly one after the other: one that

Chrome as "inactive" and one that sets it back to "active". In

production, there's some grace period before we actually set Chrome as

"inactive" (see ChromeVisibilityObserver::visibility_gap_timeout_).



The test however did not account for this, so it would close a window,

and immediately check that we are still "active". But that would

sometimes fail, because the test had only processed the first

notification (the one that sets Chrome as "inactive"), but not the

second (the one that sets Chrome back to "active").

entry.title: Add VRR frame scheduling
entry.content:
This CL makes the minimum changes to support scheduling frames in a

manner compatible with variable refresh rates. As long as the VRR

feature is enabled, the root frame sink will use a

BackToBackBeginFrameSource (as opposed to the default

DelayBasedBeginFrameSource.)



When VRR is enabled on a compatible display, the BeginFrameArgs will

use the maximum vsync interval (instead of the nominal vsync interval),

which allows the Scheduler & DisplayScheduler to set appropriately

delayed deadlines.

entry.title: Decrement active request count *after* callback
entry.content:
The documentation of CronetEngine.getActiveRequestCount() currently

states:



> Returns the number of in-flight requests. A request is in-flight if

> its start() method has been called but it hasn't reached a final state

> yet. A request reaches the final state when one of the following

> callbacks has been called



The code doesn't match the documentation. Instead of decrementing the

active request count after the callback "has been called", it decrements

the active request count before the callback is called.



This commit fixes the code to match the contract, which is likely

what users want - users are unlikely to be happy with getActiveRequestCount() returning zero while callbacks are still firing.



Also, we only decrement the count after *all* callbacks have

returned, including any "request finished listener" callbacks.

Otherwise this defeats the point of the counter, which is to wait for

*all* asynchronous background work to complete. This is somewhat

non-trivial in terms of concurrency and accounts for most of the

complexity in this change.

entry.title: COOP: restrict-properties 6/*: tokens to local and initial remote pages.
entry.content:
Send information as to what browsing context group a page lives in, at

page creation time, when a new RenderView is created. The information

is sent over mojo as part of the CreateRenderViewParams for RenderView

creation initiated by the browser, or as part of CreateNewWindowReply

for popup creation cases initiated by the renderer. It is then received

and stored on the blink::Page object.



The information itself is a bundle comprising a browsing context group

token and a CoopRelatedGroup token. This is added as a struct to

blink/common for usage in both blink core layers and content/. It is

typemapped to the mojo structures.



This patch is only interested in setting the appropriate information for

ordinary pages, created via blink::Page::CreateOrdinary(). Non-ordinary

pages, created via blink::Page::CreateNonOrdinary(), get a unique set

of tokens. Similarly, places that need to call WebView::Create()

without access to valid browsing context group information, either in test or dummy structures get a unique set of tokens. Although not

strictly representing a browsing context group, these tokens should not

cause any interference, because we do not enforce any restrictions on

cross-coop related group accesses.



This patch should not cause any behavior change. It is by itself not

sufficient to have up-to-date tokens in all blink::Pages. The following

patch deals with updating the BrowsingContextGroupInfo when a cross-

BrowsingInstance navigation occurs.



Low-Coverage-Reason: mojom_traits.cc failed parsing is linked to invalid

base::UnguessableTokens, which causes a crash. It is therefore not

testable without using DEATH CHECKS.

entry.title: dlp: Support IOTask::Resume after warning
entry.content:
An IOTask can be paused because of a naming conflict, or because there

is a policy warning (notification or dialog). There might be other

reasons in the future.



After being paused we invoke the IOTask::Resume() method which should

properly resume - in case of policy warnings, depending on the policy

type it should either continue to scanning or start the transfer.



To handle this properly, we modify PauseParams and ResumeParams to

hold either ConflictParams or PolicyParams (for now just the type of

the policy). If there is DLP or Enterprise Connectors policy, then we

will use the CopyOrMovePolicyIOTaskImpl, which can resume as explained

earlier. If no PolicyResumeParams are set, then the Resume has nothing

to do with policies, and we delegate the call to the base class

CopyOrMoveIOTaskImpl, which already "knows" how to resume after

a naming conflict, and could potentially support other pause/resume

causes in the future. It should not handle policy related resumes, so

when we detect PolicyResumeParams set in this class, we abort the task

with an error.
